<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-777-998  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 777 998.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  June 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Intelsat hires NASA to rescue Intelsat 6. (InternationalTelecommunications Satellite Organization)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     International Telecommunications Satellite OrganizationIntelsat (Artificial satellite)SatellitesMaintenance ContractsUnited States. National Aeronautics and Space Administration.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>INTELSAT HIRES NASA TO RESCUE INTELSAT 6 WASHINGTON, D.C., U.S.A., 1990 JUN13 (NB) -- International Telecommunications Satellite Organization, known asIntelsat, is offering to pay NASA $90 million to mount a spacewalk rescuemission during the February 1992 maiden flight of the shuttle Endeavour.andO;Hughes Aircraft will be awarded a contract to provide a solid-fuel boosterfor the crippled relay station, along with other required equipment.andM;Intelsat 6 was stranded March 14 when it failed to separate properly from thesecond stage of its Titan 3 launch rocket because of a faulty ejectionsystem.andP;  The only way to get the satellite away from the spent second stagewas to separate it from an on-board rocket that was to have boosted the relaystation toward its planned orbit 22,300 miles above the equator.andM;The rescue plan calls for Endeavour to carry a new kick motor into orbit, andhave its astronauts physically attach the satellite to the motor.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900615/Press Contact: Ken Atchison, NASA, 202-453-8400)</TEXT></DOC>